âœ… 3. What are BufferedReader and BufferedWriter? Why are they used?
BufferedReader reads text from a character-input stream efficiently, using a buffer.

BufferedWriter writes text to a character-output stream efficiently.

Benefits:

Faster than using FileReader/FileWriter alone because they use internal buffers.

BufferedReader provides readLine() method to read line-by-line.

âœ… 4. What's the difference between FileReader and BufferedReader?
Aspect	FileReader	BufferedReader
Speed	Slower (no buffer)	Faster (uses a buffer)
Line Reading	No readLine() method	Has readLine() method
Use Case	Small files	Large files or line-by-line reading

âœ… 5. Can we read and write to the same file simultaneously?
Technically yes, but it's not recommended because:

It can lead to data corruption or overwrite.

Java file writers/readers donâ€™t synchronize access.

ðŸ“Œ Best practice: Read into memory â†’ modify â†’ write back.

