while ((line = reader2.readLine()) != null) {
    writer.write(line);
    writer.newLine();
}
reader2.close();
writer.close();
âœ… 5. How do you handle large files (e.g., 1 GB) efficiently in Java?
Use BufferedReader â€” processes file line-by-line.

Avoid reading the whole file into memory (readAllLines()).

Consider using:

FileChannel with ByteBuffer

Memory-mapped files

Streaming APIs

âœ… 6. What are FileInputStream and FileOutputStream used for?
Used for byte stream operations (binary files).

Example: Reading/writing images, audio, video, PDF, etc.

java
Copy
Edit
FileInputStream in = new FileInputStream("source.jpg");
FileOutputStream out = new FileOutputStream("target.jpg");
int b;
while ((b = in.read()) != -1) {
    out.write(b);
}
in.close();
out.close();
âœ… 7. Difference between character streams and byte streams?
Feature	Character Stream (Reader/Writer)	Byte Stream (InputStream/OutputStream)
Data type handled	Characters (text)	Bytes (binary data)
Suitable for	Text files	Images, audio, PDF
Classes used	FileReader, FileWriter	FileInputStream, FileOutputStream

âœ… 8. How do you store objects in a file? (Serialization)
java
Copy
Edit
ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(new FileOutputStream("object.dat"));
oos.writeObject(myObject);
oos.close();

ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(new FileInputStream("object.dat"));
MyClass obj = (MyClass) ois.readObject();
ois.close();
The class must implement Serializable interface.

âœ… 9. How do you encrypt file content before saving?
Use a simple algorithm or javax.crypto APIs.

java
Copy
Edit
String content = "Secret";
String encrypted = Base64.getEncoder().encodeToString(content.getBytes());

FileWriter fw = new FileWriter("secret.txt");
